			<title>[제임스 베이커 판사 인터뷰] AI는 더이상 피할 수 없는 현실, 제대로 쓰는 법 찾으면 된다</title>
			<description>&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div class="cheditor-caption-wrapper" style="text-align: center;"&gt;   &lt;figure class="cheditor-caption" style="background-color: #f0f0f0; max-width: 600px; margin: 0px auto; display: inline-block; width: 100%;"&gt;      &lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/images/198815_1(1).jpg" alt="198815_1.jpg" style="width: 100%; height: auto;" /&gt;      &lt;figcaption class="cheditor-caption-text" style="margin: 10px; text-align: left; font-size:14px; line-height: 1.6em"&gt;제임스 베이커 판사가 2019년 5월 미국변호사협회(ABA)가 주최한 ‘사이버 미래에 대한 대담’에서 마무리 발언을 하고 있다.《ABA Rule of Law Initiative》&lt;/figcaption&gt;   &lt;/figure&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- 챗GPT의 등장으로 AI 기술이 급속도로 발전하고 있다. 법조인들은 어떻게 대처해야 할까?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“AI법 강의를 시작할 때면 나도 학생들에게 같은 질문을 한다. AI가 사람보다 잘하는 것이 무엇인지, 사람이 AI보다 잘하는 것이 무엇인지, 어떤 분야의 법이 성장하고 퇴보할지를 질문한다. 나도 나만의 대답을 갖고 있지만 법조인들은 자신만의 답을 찾으시길 바란다. 자신의 운명을 스스로 개척해 나가길 바라는 마음에서다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;하지만 짚고 넘어가야 할 부분이 있다. ‘AI가 사람보다 더 잘하는 것’이라는 질문은 잘못되었다. 사람과 기계는 팀을 이뤄 성장하기 때문이다. 사람은 AI를 잘 다루고 훈련해야 그만큼 자신만의 경쟁력을 확보할 수 있다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI가 어쏘 변호사를 대체하고 변호사 일자리를 위협하리라는 우려가 있다.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“내 생각은 결국 변호사라는 직업을 떠나 사람이 잘하는 것이 무엇인지를 질문해 봐야 한다는 것이다. 만약 당신이 젊은 어쏘 변호사라면 팀 구성 · 공감 · 인지·문제 발견·판단 능력에 집중하라고 강조하고 싶다. 변호사는 AI 도구가 새로 등장할 때면 어떻게 활용해야 할지를 익혀야 비로소 전문가가 될 수 있다. 그래서 젊은 변호사에게 해주고 싶은 조언은 단지 문서만 검토하는 전문가가 되어서는 안 되고 문서를 검토할 때 AI를 어떻게 잘 활용할지 아는 전문가가 되어야 한다는 것이다. 한 마디로, 사람이 잘할 수 있는 일을 잘해야 한다. 또한 기계와 팀을 이루어 사람만이 할 수 있는 일을 잘해야 한다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;로펌은 수직적 조직인 경우가 대부분인데 이제는 변화해야 한다. AI를 활용할 때, 가장 젊은 어쏘 변호사가 AI를 도구로 어떻게 활용하고, 결과를 어떻게 해석해야 하고, AI가 만든 증거들을 어떻게 이해해야 하는지 가장 잘 아는 사람일 수 있다. 로펌은 AI 활용에 적합한 사람들이 젊은 변호사와 어쏘 변호사일 수 있다는 점을 명심해야 한다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- 한국에서는 일부 변호사단체가 AI 도입에 저항하고 있다. 미국도 유사한 문제를 겪고 있는지 궁금하다.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“흥미로운 질문이다. 새로운 기술이 등장하면 사회에 저항이 나타나는 건 당연하다. 특히 새로운 기술이 파괴적이고 혁신적일 때 기술에 대한 저항이 등장한다. 스티븐 호킹 박사는 ‘강력한 AI가 인류에게 최선이 될 수 있고 최악이 될 수도 있다’고 말했다. 그러나 어쨌든 AI는 여기에 존재한다. 유능하고 성실한 변호사는 고객을 변호하기 위해 모든 수단을 사용할 의무가 있다. 그렇기에 AI는 필연적으로 법조계 관행이 될 것이다. 이제는 이 도구를 현명하게 이용하는 것이 필요하다. AI에 저항하거나 피하지 말아야 한다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- 변호사는 AI를 어떻게 효율적으로 활용할 수 있을까. 또 변호사는 AI시대에서 어떻게 경쟁력을 가질 수 있나.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“AI에는 수많은 기술이 접목돼 있어 AI를 이해하는 건 쉽지 않다. AI에서는 사람의 통제력과 기계의 자율성이 충돌한다. 사람이 많이 통제할수록 AI가 결정하는 부분이 줄어들게 된다. 또한, AI는 사람과 같이 편견을 갖고 있는데 오히려 사람보다 더 다양한 형태의 편견을 갖고 있다. 변호사는 이런 점들을 유의하며 AI를 활용해야 한다. 이뿐만 아니라 AI가 학습한 데이터의 출처가 어딘지, 그 데이터의 장단점은 무엇인지 끊임없이 확인하고 의심해야 한다. 한마디로 변호사는 AI의 구상부터 시험, 사용, 검증까지 전 단계에 거쳐 AI 기술을 이해할 필요가 있다. AI를 잘 이해하고 활용한다면 자신만의 경쟁력을 확보할 수 있다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI가 학습하는 양질의 데이터를 강조했다. AI가 양질의 데이터를 학습하기 위해 어떻게 해야 하나.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“변호사는 AI에 사용된 데이터가 옳은지를 항상 확인해야 한다. 그렇기 위해서 올바른 질문을 해야 한다. 이를 위해 변호사는 자신이 일하는 방법과 장소를 바꿀 필요가 있다. 예를 들어, AI 연구소를 직접 방문해 질문하고 답을 듣는 것이다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;입법부의 역할도 중요하다. 입법부가 법률을 통해 데이터 관리 방안을 마련해야 한다. 누가 데이터를 소유할지, 얼마나 오래 보관할지, 어떤 방식으로 데이터를 수집할지 등 가이드라인을 마련해야 한다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;결국 법조계가 할 수 있는 일은 AI 사용 과정에서 면밀하게 검증하는 것이다. AI를 의심하고 질문해야 한다. 그에 대한 답을 듣지 못해도 괜찮다. 다만, 의심하지 않는 것이 문제가 될 뿐이다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI 환각 현상(AI가 허구의 가짜 정보를 만드는 현상)이 문제가 되고 있다. AI가 가짜 판례를 만들었다는 보도가 나온 적도 있다. 대응책이 뭔가.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“변호사는 자신들이 이해하지 못한 기술을 이용하지 않으면 된다. 유능하고 성실한 변호사라면 보고서를 제출하기 전에 자신이 인용한 사건을 직접 검토하고 파악한다. 플로리다주 변호사감시위원회는 올해 1월 변호사를 상대로 권고 사안을 발표했다. 변호사가 AI를 활용할 때 인용된 사건을 검토하는 노력이 필요하다고 강조하면서 고객의 비밀 유지 의무도 유의하라고 했다. 많은 생성형 AI 플랫폼은 입력한 정보를 시스템에 통합하는데 이때 고객 비밀 유지를 위반할 수 있기에 각별히 유의하라고 강조했다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI 도입으로 새로운 유형의 사건들이 등장할 것이라고 했다. 사법부에 어떤 변화를 일으킬 것이라고 예상하나.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“앞으로 판사들은 4가지 핵심 임무를 수행하게 된다. 첫째, 판사는 AI 증거의 문지기(Gatekeeper) 역할을 할 것이다. 판사는 AI가 만든 증거들이 법정에서 언제 인정되고 어떤 절차에 따라 인정돼야 하는지를 결정할 것이다. 둘째, 미국에서 판사는 원칙적으로 헌법상 권리와 법적 권리를 지키는 수호자(Guardian)이다. 판사는 정부 또는 다른 기관이 AI를 활용하는 때 법적 권리를 침해하지 않는지 판단해야 할 의무가 있다. 셋째, 판사는 AI의 소비자(Consumer)이다. 법조인들이 컴퓨터를 활용해 업무를 수행하는 것처럼 판사도 업무에 AI를 활용할 것이다. 넷째, 판사는 번역가(Translator)가 되어야 한다. AI 기술이 무엇인지, 그것이 무엇을 하는지, 그리고 그것이 믿을만한지 의견을 내야 한다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- 판사가 AI 활용할 때 조심할 점은.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“나는 판사가 AI 기술을 예측 수단으로 활용하는 데 회의적이다. 예를 들어 보석, 가석방, 재범 위험을 예측하는 것과 관련해서다. 행동을 본질적으로 예측하기란 어렵다. 판사는 알고리즘과 데이터 등 AI가 사용되는 목적을 살펴보면서도 판사들이 하는 본연의 역할을 해야 한다. 판단력을 잃지 말아야 한다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;2023년 10월 23일 미국 정부는 ‘AI 행정명령’을 발표했다. AI를 형사 재판에 활용할 때 편견과 같은 위험 요소를 줄일 방법을 연구하라는 내용이 들어갔다. 그만큼 행정부도 재판 절차에서 AI 활용이 문제가 될 수 있음을 인지하고 있다는 뜻이다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI의 결정에 인종, 성별 등 편견이 내재할 수 있다는 우려가 있다. 이런 문제는 어떻게 해결해야 할까.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“변호사와 판사로서 우리는 사람을 성별, 인종, 종교를 토대로 편견을 갖는다고 생각한다. 그러나 AI에는 더 다양한 편견들이 존재한다. AI 결과의 품질과 정확성에 복합적 요인이 영향을 미친다. 그 요인에 통계적 편향과 일반적 편향이 모두 포함되어 있어 AI는 더 넓은 범주의 편견을 갖게 된다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;AI의 편견은 미묘하고 식별하기 어렵다. 예를 들어, 사람이 일자리 지원을 위해 사이트를 접속한 기록 또는 소셜 미디어를 통해 가입한 기록 등 연령과 관련 없는 데이터 학습으로 고용 심사 알고리즘을 만들 때 연령차별 문제가 나타날 수 있다. 나이가 많은 사람은 컴퓨터 브라우저를 사용하는 경향이 있고 젊은 사람들은 모바일 브라우저를 선호하는 경향이 있다는 것이 정확한 연령 데이터가 아니기 때문이다. 네트워크 신경망의 경우에도 신경망의 블랙박스 내 결과가 도출됐을 때 어떤 편견이 개입됐는지 분별할 수가 없다. 변호사와 판사는 편견을 확인하기 위해 질문을 잘해야 한다. 비판적이고 논리적인 사고를 토대로 AI에 끊임없이 질문해야 한다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;- AI 전문가로서, 한국 법조인에게 해주고 싶은 조언은?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;“전문가라고 불러줘서 감사하지만 나는 AI를 배우는 학생이다. 이 분야는 급속도로 성장하고 있다. 그래서 나도 같은 내용으로 AI 발표를 해본 적이 없다. AI에는 확답도 없다. 확답이 있다고 생각하는 사람들은 조심할 필요가 있다.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;한국은 기술 강국이다. 내가 해주고 싶은 말은‘과감하게 도전하라!’이다. 변호사는 변호사가 잘할 수 있는 부분을, 판사는 판사가 잘할 수 있는 부분을 놓치지 말고 항상 질문하시길 바란다. 내가 그랬듯이 모두가 할 수 있다.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom:15px; padding:15px; background-color:#fdf3d8"&gt;   &lt;b&gt;제임스 베이커 판사는 &lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;제임스 베이커 판사는 예일대학교 로스쿨을 졸업해 법조인의 길에 들어섰다. 이전에 미연방 군사 항소법원 판사로 15년간 근무했으며, 마지막 5년 동안 수석 판사를 역임했다.&lt;br /&gt;미국 변호사협회 법률 및 국가 안보 상임위원회 의장을 맡고 있다. 또 예일대 조지타운대 로스쿨 등 여러 대학의 강단에 섰다.&lt;br /&gt;2017~2018년에는 MIT 국제 연구 센터에서 인공지능을 연구했다. 지난해 미연방 사법센터의 의뢰로 책 《미연방 판사를 위한 인공지능 입문서(An Introduction to Artificial Intelligence for Federal Judges)》를 집필했다.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;hr style="height: 1px; background-color: #999999; border: none;" /&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center; "&gt;   &lt;b&gt;[인터뷰 영어원문]&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;1. You have authored several books on AI. As a law school professor with a background as a judge, this is quite an extraordinary path. What motivated you to write about AI?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As I recount in my book, The Centaur’s Dilemma, in 2017, I invited the Director of IARPA (the Intelligence Advanced Research Projects Activity) to give a presentation to the American Bar Association about emerging and disruptive technologies. As is the case with Jason Matheny, he gave a brilliant presentation. At the end, I asked, “Jason, you are in a room full of lawyers. What do you need from us?” His response: “We need someone to look at how national security law and ethics should apply to AI.” Two weeks later, Jason asked to have coffee with me because he said he had found the right lawyer to take on the project. After twenty minutes of coffee, my curiosity got to me: “Who did you get?” I asked. His response: “You.” I responded, “But I cannot even spell AI.” However, I took the project on because I feel responsibility as a public servant and professor to teach students what they need to know for the 21st century and AI is at the top of my list.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;What is the message? Don’t have coffee with Jason Matheny, but also anyone can learn about AI if I can and if you are a lawyer and care about your profession you must learn about AI.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;2. With the rapid advancement of AI technologies, including the recent emergence of ChatGPT, how do you foresee AI impacting the legal field? What changes do you anticipate for the work of lawyers and judges?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is the question with which I start my AI law classes. I ask, what is AI better at than humans, what are humans better at than AI, and knowing that, what skills should you learn in law school and what areas of law will grow, and which areas shrink. I have my answers. But I want the students and your readers to answer the question, not rely on my answer, because I want students and readers to understand and own their own destiny.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;But I should also say, asking “what is AI better at” is a trick question. Because we are really talking about human-machine teaming. It is also a trick question, because AI is only better at anything if it is well designed, properly trained, and properly used and understood – by humans. I will have more in response to this question in a moment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;3. There are concerns that AI could replace associate lawyers, posing a threat to their jobs. What are your thoughts on this issue?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I get this question from librarians as well. My thought is to return to the last question and ask what are humans better at than lawyers. If you are a young lawyer, let’s say an associate, I would focus on those skills – like team building, emotional intelligence, cognitive recognition, issue spotting, and judgment. Lawyers also need to be experts at how to use new and emerging AI tools. Thus, my advice to younger lawyers is don’t become an expert in reviewing documents, become an expert in how to use AI tools to review documents, including selecting those documents for human review and analysis. In short, be good at what only humans can do, or what only humans can do when teamed with machines. (I have a list).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Remember this as well. As a judge I got to work with wonderful law clerks who had just graduated from law school. In theory, as a judge I knew more law than they did. I had seen more cases. But guess what they knew more about on day one? Technology and especially social media. At our court, which handled hundreds of electronic search and seizure appeals this was essential technical knowledge to go along with my legal knowledge. Associates should not discount what they might bring to your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Law firms, which tend to be hierarchical, are going to have to change how they practice. When AI is in play, it may be that the youngest associate is the lawyer with the best understanding of how to use AI tools and how to interpret their output, or how to understand AI generated evidence. Law firms will need to make sure the right people are in the room (or in court) and the right people may be the youngest lawyers and associates.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;4. The Korean Bar Association has been resistant to the introduction of AI. Are similar issues present in American legal associations, and if so, how are they being addressed?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Interesting question. Yes. Resistance to technological change is normative for many societies as well as the legal profession. I still use a typewriter. (Okay that is a joke). Resistance to new technologies is even more common when those technologies are disruptive. Stephen Hawking said, “The rise of powerful AI will either be the best or the worst thing ever to happen to humanity.” Lawyers who are following AI may feel the same way about AI’s pending impact on the legal profession.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;But AI is here. It will inevitably be part of legal practice because competent and diligent lawyers have a duty to use all the tools available to represent their clients. The key is to use those tools wisely and well, in other words, competently.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;My advice: Don’t resist it or avoid it, shape it. That was Jason Matheny’s point – get involved and tell us how law and ethics should apply to AI. That is my point in the concluding chapter to The Centaur’s Dilemma. The chapter is titled “The Centaur’s Choice.” We can sit back and watch and bemoan what AI and other disruptive technologies are doing, or we can get in the arena and seek to guide the law and guide those who use AI to preferred and honorable outcomes.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;5. What approaches do you believe are necessary for lawyers to effectively utilize AI? Additionally, what skills should lawyers develop to maintain their competitiveness in the AI era?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;AI is a challenging field to understand and to regulate because AI really refers to a constellation of technologies and myriad different applications and techniques. To structure my analysis, I would do four things. First, in my view, most of the hard legal and ethical issues involving AI revolve around three buckets of issues:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;(1) &lt;/b&gt;what I call the Centaur’s Dilemma, the choice in each context as to how much human control we assert and where and how much machine autonomy we permit and where. It is a dilemma because the more human control you assert, the less advantage you may obtain from a machine’s capacity to derive meaning and make decisions instantaneously based on data.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;(2) &lt;/b&gt;Bias. As we will see in a moment, AI like humans has bias, but here there are different types of bias beyond those we usually associate with humans.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;(3)&lt;/b&gt; Data. Where it come from? Who owns it? What are its strengths and weaknesses, etc.?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Second, I would purposefully make a list and understand the strengths and weaknesses of the technology you are using. Third, I would do this with each AI application I am using or contemplating using. And four, I would need to move upstream and downstream to do so. This is a change for lawyers. I need to understand the AI from conception-to-testing-to-use-to-ongoing validation.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;A lawyer who understands and does these four things will always be valuable to a law firm and to their clients.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;6. In your book 《An Introduction to Artificial Intelligence for Federal Judges》, you mention that the introduction of AI could lead to new types of cases in court. What major changes do you foresee AI bringing to the judiciary?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In my view, judges will perform four core tasks when it comes to AI (although different judges might describe and categorize these tasks differently). First, judges are evidentiary gatekeepers. They will need to decide when AI generated evidence is admitted in court and subject to what process of authentication. Second, they are guardian of rights, in the U.S., principally constitutional rights and statutory rights. Judges, for example, will need to determine when AI is being used by the government or others in violation of rights like due process. Third, judges are or may become consumers of AI as a courthouse tool. Of course, we already are if we use computer generated spell check and grammar tools. Fourth, judges will be translators, articulating in their opinions what an AI technology is, what it does, and whether it is reliable.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;What types of cases might arise raising AI issues? My goodness, how do I begin to count the ways AI will arrive in court: Torts (think medical screening and driverless cars), criminal law (think … anything to do with pornography), copyright, free speech and First Amendment. Please see AI for Judges for more examples.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;7. What practices would be most effective for judges when using AI? Also, what precautions should be taken when incorporating AI into judicial processes?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;My co-author Professor Hobart is very skeptical about judges using AI as a predictive tool, for example, to predict bail, parole, or recidivism risk. I am too. And so is the President of the United States, which is why the AI Executive Order signed on October 30, 2023, directs extensive study on the ways AI might be used in criminal trials and the procedures that surround criminal trials and how to mitigate risks. One reason for caution is that it is inherently hard to predict behavior, and AI tools may give the process the imprimatur of data and science it does not deserve. Another reason is that there are different, subtle, and sometimes hidden ways that inappropriate factors, like race, can influence data and algorithms without the users knowing it, for example, through proxies like zip codes. Individual case determinations should be based on the merits of individual cases not generalized data sets.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;However, where I might differ from some scholars is in my willingness to consider judicial AI tools, not to predict future behavior, but to better understand and derive meaning from the data that informs judicial decisions, all transparently on the record and without relinquishing a judge’s duty to exercise his or her independent and impartial judgment.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;My advice to judges: Whatever you do, look under the hood, at the algorithmic weights and parameters, at the data, and the purposes for which an AI is used, and do what judges do – ask questions, lots of them.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;8. You have emphasized the importance of the quality and quantity of data that AI learns from. What measures should the legal community take to ensure AI has access to high-quality data?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Lawyers should start by asking the right questions to make sure that the data that is used to train, test, and validate AI is appropriate to the use. This requires lawyers to change how and where they practice; they may need to visit the AI lab, for example, to get their questions answered. I also believe it would be helpful for legislatures, including in the U.S., to pass laws delineating who owns data and for how long and in what form, who can scrape data, and what uses they can make with the data. I would also ask if certain data should be off limits, like data collected from children.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are technologists who can tell you better than I can what makes a good data set. One message here: the validation of AI and its use is a team effort. A second lesson is that it is okay for lawyers to not know the answer to an AI question. It is not okay not to ask.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;9. There are concerns that AI decisions may exhibit biases related to race, gender, and other factors. How can such biases be mitigated?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;One of the aspects about AI that is interesting, others might say problematic, is the role of bias. Here the first step is to understand that bias with AI is both the same and different from how we think about bias with humans. With humans and as lawyers and judges, we are generally thinking about the bias that might attach to a suspect class of persons based on gender, race, or religion. However, with AI there are many more types of bias that we need to look for involving both statistical bias and bias in the design and data involved that may impact the quality and accuracy of the AI output.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Two of the challenges with bias and AI are that some of the bias is subtle and hard to discern. Age discrimination, for example, might emerge in an employment screening algorithm not based on age, but based on the browser an applicant uses to apply or their use of social media. Older people tend to use the browser the computer comes with; younger people tend to switch to a preferred browser. In the case of neural networks, it is also hard, and in some cases impossible to discern on what basis the AI selected an output when that output has emerged within the “black box” of neural networks.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That is why in our work on AI, we always spell out in plain language the different types of AI bias. We also identify key questions lawyers and judges should ask to identify embedded bias. But part of the solution is for lawyers and judges to use the sort of critical and analytic thinking great lawyers are known for and ask: What factors might make the AI accurate and what factors might undermine its accuracy? That is part of the interest of AI to me, there are so many facets and angles to consider.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;10. The phenomenon of AI hallucinations is also problematic, with instances of AI generating false legal precedents. Can judges identify and filter out these hallucinations? If not, how should the judiciary respond?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Judges shouldn’t have to. Lawyers should not use technology they do not understand. Let’s call that the Know Your Technology rule, or KYT. Moreover, a competent and diligent lawyer will, of course, read all the cases cited in their brief before they file the brief. The Florida Board of Bar Overseers issued an advisory opinion in January of this year. It is clear and succinct and identifies four ethical issues for lawyers using AI: (1) competence and diligence, as just described; (2) client confidentiality; (3) advertising; and (4) billing. Many generative AI platforms incorporate what users input into the system. You can see how that could lead to arguments about the waiver of confidentiality and lead to the loss of confidentiality.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;11. As an AI expert, what advice would you offer to legal professionals in Korea?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Thank you for the moniker “expert” but I am a student of AI. We are all students of AI. The field is moving at an exponential pace. I have never given the same AI presentation twice. I would be cautious around someone who thinks they have all the AI answers. Korea is a tech savvy nation. Therefore, my advice is – dare. Jump in. Do what lawyers do and do well. Ask questions. Look under the hood. If I can do it, you can do it too. I promise.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;b&gt;12. Finally, could you share your thoughts on being invited to The Law Times' "Legal Tech &amp; AI Forum"?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;First, I am grateful. I am always grateful for the opportunity to talk to lawyers about AI. AI is here. And I deeply believe that lawyers will help to determine which fork in Stephen Hawking’s road we take. What is more, users of AI should want the AI they rely on to be as accurate as possible. The thoughtful application of law and ethics results in more accurate AI, not just more law and lawyers. Law and ethics are also what is, or should, distinguish the democratic use of AI from the authoritarian use of AI.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is my fourth trip to South Korea. I first came to South Korea as a Marine infantry officer as part of Team Spirit. South Korea is a vital U.S. ally and friend, based not just on military alliance but on an alliance of values. Law is one of those values that bond our two societies.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;AI will put strain on the law and strain on principles of democracy. It can also do great good. Let’s get to work and make sure that when we reach each fork in the AI road, we pick the path that honors our shared legal values. Thank you.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;   &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
